The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Satyam software hub in Malaysia takes off

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 Raju: Going places

 Mumbai, Sept. 10: Satyam Computer Services Ltd today announced the opening of its largest software hub outside the country. The companys 500-seat global solutions centre in Malaysia became fully operational from today. 

 We will not be able to indicate the total amount invested in the centre, but it is a sizeable investment running into multi-million dollars which we will scale up further, Indraneel Ganguli, head of global marketing and communications, Satyam Computer Services, told The Telegraph.

 The global solutions centre serves us two major purposes better manpower and the need to serve our customers more efficiently, Ganguli added.

 The centre has 300 IT engineers, mostly Malaysian. The team will support Satyams Asean, West Asian, and American customers. 

 The facility will be integrated with other Satyam centres. It will serve as a major software development centre, to bring solutions to the market more quickly through Satyams low-risk global delivery model, the company said in a release. 

 The unit is expected to create more than 500 jobs in Malaysia over the next one year. Satyam has 26 global solutions centres all over the world.

 We consider this facility to be a significant part of Satyams commitment to multi-dimensional investments in Malaysia, an excellent alternative to India for solutions development, said Satyam chairman Ramalinga Raju.

 We find the country attractive because of its advanced infrastructure, rich talent pool, competitive cost environment, and a favourable business climate. We look forward to strengthening our relationship with the Malaysian government and the professionals in the country, Raju added. 

 A memorandum of understanding was signed in December between Satyam and Multimedia Development Corporation, which oversees the MSC Malaysia programme. MSC Malaysia is a state-owned high-tech zone, covering 750 square kilometres, designed to make Malaysia a global IT leader.

 Satyam plans to employ 5,000 workers in Malaysia. It will quadruple the workforce in the first phase of development of the software unit to 2,000 by 2010.

 Satyams development and delivery centres in the US, Canada, the UK, Hungary, Egypt, the United Arab Emirates, India, China, Malaysia, Singapore and Australia serve 570 clients, including one-third of the US Fortune 500 companies.




